United Kingdom","Roddam, Northumberland, England":"Roddam, Northumberland, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stanhope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Stanhope (Durham), from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>hop</i> ‘valley’.","History: A family of this name have held the title Earl of Harrington since 1742, and were Earls of Chesterfield from 1628–1967. Philip Stanhope, 1st Earl of Chesterfield, was a Royalist soldier in the English Civil War. He was captured in 1643 and died in prison in 1656."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Maud Stanhope was born in 1265, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 6 sons with William Roddam 2nd. She died in 1297, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1265–1297":"1265–1297","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1284–1304":"1284–1304","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1289–1304":"1289–1304","1297–1327":"1297–1327","–1337":"–1337","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","ABT 1284":"umbes 1284","1289":"1289","1355":"1355","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1275":"umbes 1275","Roddam, England":"Roddam, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Roddam, Northumberland, England":"Roddam, Northumberland, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1265–1297":"1265–1297","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1284–1304":"1284–1304","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1289–1304":"1289–1304","1297–1327":"1297–1327","–1337":"–1337","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","ABT 1284":"noin 1284","1289":"1289","1355":"1355","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1275":"noin 1275","Roddam, England":"Roddam, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Roddam, Northumberland, England":"Roddam, Northumberland, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1265–1297":"1265–1297","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1275–Male":"1275–Décédé","1284–1304":"1284–1304","1287–Male":"1287–Décédé","1289–1304":"1289–1304","1297–1327":"1297–1327","–1337":"–1337","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","ABT 1284":"environ 1284","1289":"1289","1355":"1355","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1275":"environ 1275","Roddam, England":"Roddam, Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Rodda